  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense under the legislation of most countries, including China. It is defined as the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\") by disguising the true source, nature, or ownership of the funds. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers.\n\nIn China, the Criminal Law of the People's Republic of China specifically addresses money laundering in **Article 191**, which criminalizes the act of disguising or concealing the source and nature of proceeds obtained from criminal activities. Those found guilty of money laundering can face severe penalties, including imprisonment, fines, and confiscation of assets.\n\nAdditionally, China has established a robust regulatory framework to combat money laundering, including the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which requires financial institutions and certain non-financial entities to implement measures to detect and prevent money laundering.\n\nGlobally, money laundering is also recognized as a serious crime. International organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set standards and promote policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. Countries that fail to comply with these standards may face economic sanctions or other consequences.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a criminal offense under both Chinese and international law, and it is actively prosecuted to maintain the integrity of financial systems and combat organized crime.",
